Installation

Overview

We will use Laravel Sail in our development environment; below are the steps to get the incfile/atomic repo up and running.


Prerequisites

  • Git

  • Docker Desktop

  • PHP 7.4 or higher & the latest version of Composer

  • CircleCi

Create SSH Keys

Follow this guide on creating SSH keys and importing them into your GitHub account.


Import SSH Keys to GitHub

......


Fork the incfile/atomic Repo

We use the Git Forking Workflow where developers will work within their fork. When tasks are completed, pull requests should be issued back to the main repo.


To begin, fork the incfile/atomic repository to your personal GitHub account.



Clone Your Forked Repo

To get your fork out of the incfile/atomic repo onto your local machine, you can run the following commands:

cd [YOUR_PATH]
git clone git@github.com:[USERNAME]/atomic
cd atomic/


Add Upstream Repo

Adding the upstream repository to your git remotes lets you easily sync changes from incfile/atomic into your fork.

git remote add upstream git@github.com:incfile/atomic
git fetch -a upstream


Either the first time or whenever you want to merge in the changes from the incfile/master into your feature branch/local, you can run the following command: -a upstream

git pull upstream master


Docker

We need to have the repository running in Docker, to do so we will be using the laravel/sail composer package globally. You may install it by running the following command:

  composer global require laravel/sail


sh sail/init.sh

Add sail as an alias. 

As an optional step use Sail as an alias while running your project.

nano ~/.zshrc // ZSH 
nano ~/.bashrc // Ubuntu Bash 
alias sail='[ -f sail ] && sh sail || sh vendor/bin/sail' 

Setting .env Variables

You may make a copy of the .env.example file at the root of your repository and rename it to .env. This will serve as your default configuration for launching your docker containers. You may then modify the variables as you wish.


Bring Up The Machine

To set up the docker containers, you must run the following commands in the root directory of your repo:

docker-compose up

or

sail up

⌛

Be patient; this can take some time the first time you do this


To access the project routes, we must copy the following host names into our hosts' file (Windows: "C:\Windows\System32\drivers\etc\hosts", Mac OS: "/private/etc/hosts")

Executing Commands in Sail

Starting Containers


  • sail up: Allows you to initialize the containers and show logs in real time.

  • --detach or -d flags: you may also use them to start the containers in the background.

  • sail start: Used to resume previously stopped containers, also an alias of sail up --detach.


Stopping Containers

  • sail stop: Will stop the containers without destroying them.


❗

If you initialized sail using the sail up command you may also stop the containers using CTRL/CMD + C.


Destroying Containers

  • sail down: This will stop and remove the containers.


Additional Commands

You may get more context in the official documentation for Laravel Sail: https://laravel.com/docs/8.x/sail

Changes for the Automation Team (Deprecated)

Restrictions:

  • Atomic platform requires a minimum of Node 18.

Background:

The Automation Team encounters an issue where their applications necessitate Node 14, preventing them from upgrading to the required Node 18 for the Atomic platform.

Solution:

  1. Prerequisites: Ensure all existing processes are followed until the clone repository steps are completed.

  2. Manual Installation Steps: Instead of using docker-compose up, follow these manual installation steps:

    1. Install vendors:

composer install --ignore-reqs

    1. Uninstall or stop the Apache service. Note: This step could be integrated into the installation process, addressing potential unknown issues.

    2. After completing the composer installation, bring up the virtual machine:

vendor/bin/sail up

    1. If successful, access the internal bash:

./vendor/bin/sail bash

  1. Node Version Update: Install or upgrade Node to version 18 using NVM. Follow these steps:

    1. Install NVM by executing the following commands:

curl -o- https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nvm-sh/nvm/v0.39.7/install.sh | bash
export NVM_DIR="$([ -z "${XDG_CONFIG_HOME-}" ] && printf %s "${HOME}/.nvm" || printf %s "${XDG_CONFIG_HOME}/nvm")"
[ -s "$NVM_DIR/nvm.sh" ] && \. "$NVM_DIR/nvm.sh"

    1. Run the following command to install Node 18:

nvm install 18

  1. Execute Post-Installation Scripts: Once Node 18 is installed internally, execute the following scripts to load CSS, styles, and other dependencies:

    1. Install Yarn packages:

sail yarn install

    1. Run the npm scripts:

npm run dashboard:dev

    1. Execute Laravel Mix for Webpack:

php artisan webpack:run

    1. Install Cypress with force:

./node_modules/cypress/bin/cypress install --force

Error undefined T_VARIABLE


While executing composer global require laravel/sail returns the error: undefined T_VARIABLE


Solution


You will require an installer script provided by Composer, download and use it to install Composer.


  1. Make sure you're in your home directory, then retrieve the installer using curl:


cd ~
curl -sS https://getcomposer.org/installer -o /tmp/composer-setup.php


  1. Verify that the downloaded installer matches the SHA-384 hash for the latest installer found on the Composer Public Keys / Signatures page. To facilitate the verification step, you can use the following command to obtain the latest hash from the Composer page and store it in a shell variable:


HASH=`curl -sS https://composer.github.io/installer.sig`


  1. Execute the following PHP code, as provided in the Composer download page, to verify that the installation script is safe to run:


php -r "if (hash_file('SHA384', '/tmp/composer-setup.php') === '$HASH') { echo 'Installer verified'; } else { echo 'Installer corrupt'; unlink('composer-setup.php'); } echo PHP_EOL;"


  1. The following output will be shown:


Installer verified

$ sudo usermod -aG docker $USER

sudo chmod 666 /var/run/docker.sock

Docker Cleanup

Pruning Unused Docker Objects

Overview

Pruning cleans up unused Docker objects, including containers, networks, images, and volumes. This action helps reclaim disk space and should be performed regularly or when facing disk space issues.


Step-by-Step Guide:

1. Prune Everything (Recommended for Immediate Cleanup)

    • Open Terminal.

    • Execute the following command:

docker system prune

⚠️ Confirm the action when prompted to remove all stopped containers, unused networks, and dangling images.



2. Prune Only Unused Images (For More Targeted Cleanup)

    • Open Terminal.

    • Execute the following command:

docker image prune

    • Confirm the action when prompted to remove unused Docker images.


3. Prune Unused Volumes

    • Open Terminal.

  • Execute the following command:

docker volume prune

  • Confirm the action when prompted to remove unused Docker volumes.

Note: Pruning unused volumes can be particularly useful when dealing with volumes no longer in use, such as those associated with old containers.


Increasing Disk Space Allocated to Docker

Steps to Increase Disk Space:

  • Open Docker Desktop.

  • Go to Preferences.


  • Navigate to the 'Resources' tab.

  • Adjust the slider under 'Disk Image Size' to increase the storage allocated to Docker.

  • Apply and restart Docker for changes to take effect.


Best Practices

  • Regular Maintenance: Schedule regular pruning to manage disk space efficiently.

  • Monitor Disk Usage: Regularly check the disk space used by Docker, especially when working with large images or numerous containers.

  • Backup Important Data: Always back up important data before performing operations that might result in data loss, such as pruning.


Conclusion

Managing disk space is crucial for effectively operating Docker environments on macOS. By following these steps, users can ensure that Docker runs smoothly without running into disk space limitations. This update ensures that the docker volume prune command and its utility in managing disk space effectively within Docker environments.


Updating to PHP 8.1

Objective

This document provides a guide on updating the application to use PHP 8.1, detailing steps from downloading the latest code from the main repository to rebuilding the container.


Prerequisites

  • Ensure you have access to the main repository.

  • Docker is installed and configured on your system.


Steps

1 Sync with the Main Repository

  • Navigate to Atomic repo.

  • Pull the latest code from the main repository to ensure you have the most recent updates and dependencies:

git checkout master
git pull upstream master

2. Update the PHP Version in the Dockerfile (optional)

  • Open the Dockerfile located at the root of your project.

  • Modify the PHP version to 8.1. Your updated line should look like this:

 FROM php:8.1-fpm


icon:fas:info

Use the Dockerfile phpfpm


3. Update Dependencies (optional)

  • Open your composer.json file.

  • Ensure all dependencies are compatible with PHP 8.1.

  • Run:

   composer update

to update packages if needed.


4. Rebuild the Docker Container

After updating to PHP 8.1, you must rebuild the Docker container to apply the new PHP version.

  • In your terminal, navigate to your project directory.

  • Run the following command to stop the current container:

   docker-compose down --rmi all --volumes --remove-orphans

  • Then rebuild and start the updated container:

   docker-compose up --build -d


5. Verify the Update

  • Confirm that the application is running with PHP 8.1 by executing:

   sail php -v

This should display PHP version 8.1.




Best Practice Guidelines

As developers, we should always attempt to write our code in a way that another developer could understand it; we need to make it as readable as possible without necessarily adding comments to it. Let's think we were writing a book; the person reading it has no coding knowledge. 📖



Naming Conventions

"What the F**k is $var?"

Every single Incfile developer. (As of June 2021)


Naming things is said to be one of the hardest things in programming; that's why we have this document. Please do your best to follow it. 🙏🏼


// Good
Auth::user()
	->roles()
	->whereHas([
		'permissions' => function ($permission) {
			$permission->where('name', 'comment posts');
		},
	])
	->get();


This can be read like: "Authenticated user roles where the role has permission to comment on posts, get all of those roles".


// Bad
User::find(session()->get('user_id'))
	->userRoles()
	->whereHas([
		'rolePermissions' => function ($query) {
			$query->where('permission', 'comment posts');
		},
	])
	->get();


This would be read like this: "Find user using the user id in the session, find that user's roles where that user role has a role permission, make a query on each of those permissions where the permission is to comment on posts, finally get all of those user roles."


We can get the good example's result by following a few simple rules on how to name things.


Coding Styles


  • Classes must be named CamelCase with capitalized first letter.

  • Functions must be named camelCase.

  • Constants must be named SNAKE_CASE and uppercased.

  • Properties & Variables must be named camelCase.


Guidelines


  • Use understandable variable names:


$firstName = 'John';
$lastName = 'Doe';

// Good
$fullName = "{$firstName} {$lastName}";

// Bad
$fn = "{$firstName} {$lastName}";


  • Use understandable function names:


class Email
{
	private string $to;
	private string $from;
	private string $body;

	public function __construct(string $to, string $from, string $body)
	{
		$this->to = $to;
		$this->from = $from;
		$this->body = $body;
	}

	// Good
	public function send(): void
	{
		mail($this->to, $this->from, $this->body);
	}

	// Bad
	public function handle(): void
	{
		mail($this->to, $this->from, $this->body);
	}
}

$email = new Email('john.doe@test.com', 'jane.doe@test.com', 'Hello!');

// Good
$email->send();

// Bad
$email->handle();


Use constants instead of magic numbers:


// Good
$user->update([
	'role_id' => Role::ADMIN, // 1
]);

// Bad
$user->update([
	'role_id' => 1, // ???
]);


  • Don't add unnecessary context:


// Good
class Address
{
	public $street;
	public $city;
	public $state;
	public $country;
	public $zip;
}

// Bad
class Address
{
	public $addressStreet;
	public $addressCity;
	public $addressState;
	public $addressCountry;
	public $addressZip;
}


  • Avoid negative conditional functions:


// Good
public static function exists($bar): bool
{
	// ...
}

// Check existence
if (Foo::exists($bar)) {
	// ...
}

// Check inexistence
if (!Foo::exists($bar)) {
	// ...
}

// Bad
public static function doesNotExist($bar): bool
{
	// ...
}

// Check existence
if (!Foo::doesNotExist($bar)) {
	// ...
}

// Check inexistence
if (Foo::doesNotExist($bar)) {
	// ...
}


Laravel


Laravel has some of its own naming conventions in order to make our lives easier, if we follow them, it will not only make us more productive but also make our code a lot more readable.


Controllers


  • Controller classes must be CamelCaseController, capitalized and singular and must be suffixed with "Controller".


Blade


  • Blade view files must be named snake_case and suffixed with ".blade.php".


Database


  • Tables must be snake_case and pluralized.

  • Intermediate tables must be snake_case, ordered alphabetically and singular.

  • Columns must be snake_case and singular.

  • PK must be named "id".

  • FK must be singular of the foreign table, suffixed with "_id".


E.g., A user has many roles and a role can belong to many users.


// User
Schema::create('users', function (Blueprint $table) {
	$table->increments('id'); // PK
	$table->string('email');
	$table->string('password');
});

// Roles
Schema::create('roles', function (Blueprint $table) {
	$table->increments('id'); // PK
	$table->string('name');
});

// Intermediate: Many Users to Many Roles
Schema::create('role_user', function (Blueprint $table) {
	$table->string('role_id');
	$table->string('user_id');
});


Eloquent


  • Model classes must be named CamelCase, capitalized and singular.

  • Model attributes should be snake_case.

  • Model relationships should be defined camelCase as if they were normal functions.


Whenever we will be requesting an attribute from eloquent we will be using the snake_case naming convention. That is a good way for the developer to determine that the attribute is coming form the database and is a direct implementation of eloquent.


Now let's define the Eloquent model relationships for the example above ☝️ .


// User
class User extends Model
{
	public function roles()
	{
		return $this->belongsToMany(Role::class);
	}
}

// Roles
class Role extends Model
{
	public function users()
	{
		return $this->belongsToMany(User::class);
	}
}


If we wouldn't have followed the naming conventions that Laravel provides for us, we would have to define some additional properties in our model and pass some extra attributes into our relationship methods.


Artisan Commands


  • Artisan command names must be kebab-case.


Routing


  • Routes must be defined as kebab-case.

  • Route names must be camelCase.

  • Route params must be camelCase.

  • Routes must not start with '/' unless the route is an empty string.


Vue.js


Vue.js also has some of its own naming conventions that help prevent errors and console warnings.


In Javascript, camelCase is the standard, in HTML it’s kebab-case. Therefore, we use them accordingly.


Component names should always be multi-word, except for root components, and built-in components provided by Vue, such as <transition> or <component>.


This prevents conflict with existing and future HTML elements since all HTML elements are a single word.


  • Component names should always be multi-word and use full words instead of abbreviations. This prevents conflict with existing and future HTML elements since all HTML elements are a single word.

  • Global components that apply app-specific styling and conventions should all begin with the Base prefix.

  • Filenames for single-file components must be UpperCamelCase .

  • Tightly coupled child components should include the parent component name as a prefix instead of nesting the children in subdirectories.

  • Props should use camelCase during declaration and kebab-case in templates.

  • Events should be named using kebab-case.

  • We must always use directive shorthands instead of default directive definitions.

Example:

// Good
<template>
  <div class="modal" :class="{'hidden': isHidden}">
    <base-card>
      <template #header>
        <base-card-header>
          <button class="close" @click="$emit('hide-modal')">X</button>
        </base-card-header>
      </template>
      <!-- Body -->
      <template #footer>
        <base-card-footer>
          <!-- Footer -->
        </base-card-footer>
      </template>
    </base-card>
  </div>
</template>

<script>
import BaseCard from 'components/BaseCard';
import BaseCardHeader from 'components/BaseCardHeader';
import BaseCardFooter from 'components/BaseCardFooter';

export default {
  name: 'BaseModal',
  components: {
    'base-card': BaseCard,
    'base-card-header': BaseCardHeader,
    'base-card-footer': BaseCardFooter,
  },
  props: {
    isHidden: {
      type: Boolean,
      default: true,
    },
  }
}
</script>


// Bad
<template>
  <div class="modal" v-bind:class="{'hidden': IsHidden}">
    <Card>
      <template v-slot:header>
        <Header>
          <button class="close" @click="$emit('hideModal')">X</button>
        </Header>
      </template>
      <!-- Body -->
      <template #footer>
        <Footer>
          <!-- Footer -->
        </Footer>
      </template>
    </Card>
  </div>
</template>

<script>
import Card from 'components/card';
import Header from 'components/card-header';
import Footer from 'components/footer';

export default {
  name: 'BaseModal',
  components: {
    Card,
    Header,
    Footer,
  },
  props: {
    is_hidden: {
      type: Boolean,
      default: true,
    },
  }
}
</script>

Type Hinting

⚠️

This document is based on PHP version 7.2


Type hinting in PHP will allow us to debug our code easier and catch bugs before they bite.


To help enforce this we must add the declare(strict_types=1); line at the beginning of each php file, right after the opening <?php tag.


<?php

declare(strict_types=1);

class Foo {
	// ...
}


General Rules


  • Nullable type hinting: Always use the ? syntax before the variable type.


// Good
public ?string $foo;

// Bad
public string|null $foo;


  • Void return type: If a function doesn't return anything, type-hint the return type to void.


// Good
public function doSomething(): void
{
	// Do something without returning anything.
}


  • Always use type hinting over DocBlocks.


// Good
class Foo
{
    public string $bar;
}

// Bad
class Foo
{
    /** @var string */
    public $bar;
}


  • In PHP 7.2 we are still limited to the basics of type hinting, we cannot unite multiple types.


// Good
/** @param int|string $number */
public function toInt($number): int
{
	return (int) $number;
}


The reason why this is good is that in PHP 7.2 we can't do toInt(int|string $number).


DocBlocks


Don't use docblocks for methods that can be fully type hinted (unless you need a description). Only add a description when it provides more context than the method signature itself. Use full sentences for descriptions, including a period in the end.


class Url
{
    public static function fromString(string $url): Url
    {
        // ...
    }
}

// Bad
class Url
{
    /**
     * Create a url from a string.
     *
     * @param string $url
     *
     * @return \Spatie\Url\Url
     */
    public static function fromString(string $url): Url
    {
        // ...
    }
}


In the bad example, the description is redundant and the method is fully type-hinted.


  • Always use fully qualified names in docblocks.


// Good
/**
 * @param string $url
 *
 * @return \App\Models\User
 */

// Bad
/**
 * @param string $foo
 *
 * @return User
 */


  • When possible, docblocks should be written on one line.


// Good
/** @test */

// Bad
/**
 * @test
 */


  • If a variable has multiple types, the most commonly occurring type should be first.


// Good
/** @var \App\Models\User|null */

// Bad
/** @var null|\App\Models\User */


External References:


  • PHP Type Hinting: https://www.phpclasses.org/blog/post/1047-php-8-type-hinting.html

  • Spatie Best Practices: https://spatie.be/guidelines/laravel-php#typed-properties

  • Official PHPDocumentor: https://docs.phpdoc.org/latest/guide/guides/docblocks.html


Pull Requests

📓 Pull Request


Review your own code first


Whenever you publish your Pull Request, open it in your browser and review it as if it was someone else’s.


Write a clear description


Always try to fill all of the PR templates. Explain what the changes achieve at a high level and why you are making these changes.


Assume your reviewer does not have any context of what you worked on, so you should help them to understand.


PR description should always have a link to the ClickUp task.


Separate functional and non-functional changes


  • Separate functional and non-functional changes

    • Avoid mixing whitespace/reformat/refactor changes with functional changes.

    • It’s easier to review two lines of code than a whole file with format changes plus the actual functionality change.

  • Refactoring, code formatting

    • Code Refactoring or formatting, should be sent in a separate PR.

    • This way we know that the behavior won’t change.

Rules for writing your commit

Limit the subject line to 50 characters

Keeping subjects lines at 50 characters helps commit readability and forces you to explain what is going on on your change.


If you struggle summarizing your commit in 50 characters, this might imply you are commiting too many changes at once. Try to commit more often.


There are some special cases where you might feel the need to explain why a change was made, in those cases, you can add a body for your commit:


git commit -m "Update frontend validations on Annual Report" -m "We decided to refector to validations modules, this way we can re-use these validation rules"


In a git log this will display as:


> git log

Author: Ricardo Hernandez <ricardohs35@gmail.com>
Date:   Mon Jun 23 11:45:40 2021

    Update frontend validations on Annual Report

    We decided to refector to validations modules, this way we can re-use these validation rules


Orthography matters


Capitalize your subject.


# good
Create BaseLoading component

# bad
create BaseLoading component


Don't end the subject with a period.


# good
Update frontend validations on Annual Report

# not recomended
update frontend validations on Annual Report.


Capitalizing enhances readability. Remeber, subjects do not have line breaks, so avoiding period at the end gives you an extra character for your subject 😛


Use imperative mood in the subject line


Write your subject as if you are giving an order, starting with a verb. Examples:


# good
Refactor subsystem X for readability
Update getting started documentation
Remove deprecated methods
Release version 1.0.0

# bad
Fixed bug with Y
Changing behavior of X
More fixes for broken stuff
Sweet new API methods


Remember that writing meaningful commits could be very helpful in the future when we are trying to understand a change or searching for bugs.


You are very welcome to use https://github.com/carloscuesta/gitmoji-cli

Deploy to Production Front-End

CI/CD Pipeline Documentation

Overview

This document provides an overview of the CI/CD pipeline used for the development, testing, and deployment processes. The pipeline automates builds, tests, and deployments for three environments: Dev, Staging, and Production. Each environment operates independently to ensure reliability, scalability, and proper testing.


Environments

Dev (Development)

Purpose: A less formal environment where developers validate their changes and ensure functionality during early stages.

  • Access:

    • Accessible to developers to verify builds.

    • Publicly accessible via URL: dev.site.bizee.com.

  • Characteristics:

    • Focuses on development and initial tests.

    • Allows for faster iteration of changes.

  • May contain incomplete features.


Staging

Purpose: A formal testing environment, designed to replicate production as closely as possible for final QA validation.

  • Access:

    • Publicly accessible via URL: staging.site.bizee.com.

    • Open to anyone with the URL but not indexed by Google to avoid SEO issues.

  • Characteristics:

    • Mimics production in terms of infrastructure and functionality.

    • Used for performance, integration, and usability testing.

    • Ensures all changes are validated before deployment to production.

Production

Purpose: The live environment where the application is available to end users.

  • Access:

    • Publicly accessible via URL: site.bizee.com.

  • Characteristics:

    • Stable, optimized for user traffic.

    • Features redundancy via AWS EC2 and a load balancer to ensure high availability.


Pipeline Flow

Trigger

  • The pipeline starts when a Pull Request (PR) is merged into the respective branch (Dev, Staging, or Production ).


Envoyer.io

Envoyer.io handles the preparation phase of the pipeline:

  • Build Dependencies: Installs PHP and Node.js dependencies using package managers (e.g., Composer, npm).

  • Upload Build Assets to S3: Uploads CSS, JS, and Fonts to AWS S3.

  • Cache Refresh: Clears and updates the Statamic CMS cache to reflect new changes.

  • Automated Tests: Runs unit, integration, or other automated tests to validate functionality.


Forge

Forge manages the deployment phase for each environment:

  • Dev Deployment: Deploys to the development environment (dev.site.bizee.com).

  • Staging Deployment: Deploys to the staging environment (staging.site.bizee.com).

  • Production Deployment: Deploys to the production environment (site.bizee.com).


AWS EC2 and Load Balancer

  • Production Only:

  • The application is deployed to two AWS EC2 instances for redundancy.

  • An AWS Load Balancer distributes traffic between the two instances, ensuring high availability and scalability.


Assets in S3

Build Assets

  • Content: CSS, JS, and Fonts.

  • Lifecycle:

    • Automatically replaced during each new build.

    • Old assets are deleted to maintain a clean and efficient deployment.


CMS Content (Images and Videos)

  • Content: Images and videos used across all pages.

  • Lifecycle:

    • Uploaded directly via the CMS (Statamic) when new content is added.

    • No automated cleanup occurs since these are considered permanent assets managed through the CMS.


Key Features

Environment Isolation

  • Each environment (Dev, Staging, Production) runs on its own independent AWS EC2 instance, ensuring complete isolation.

  • This separation minimizes risks and allows realistic testing without affecting production.


Public Access

  • Dev and Staging URLs are public but:

    • Dev: For developers to validate their work.

    • Staging: For QA and stakeholders to test final versions.

    • Not indexed by Google to avoid impacting SEO.


Automated Cleanup

  • During each build, CSS, JS, and Fonts are replaced with new versions.

  • This ensures only relevant assets are served to users, keeping deployments clean.


Pipeline Diagram

Visual Representation

Below is a visual representation of the CI/CD pipeline:



Future Considerations

  1. Monitoring

    1. Add tools like AWS CloudWatch or Datadog to monitor the health of EC2 instances and track performance metrics.

  2. Security:

    1. Ensure staging and production URLs are protected against unauthorized access if sensitive data is involved.

    2. Use AWS IAM roles for access management to S3 and EC2 resources.

  3. Automation:

    1. Automate testing workflows further to improve efficiency.

    2. Consider adding performance and stress testing in the staging environment.


Conclusion

This CI/CD pipeline ensures smooth transitions between environments, reliable builds, and proper asset management. By isolating environments and leveraging AWS infrastructure, the system supports scalability and minimizes risks during deployment.

Feature Flags

Steps to add a feature flag

Create the feature flag.

Create your feature flag row on feature_flags table through a migration. Please use aUPPER_CASE naming convention, e.g., MY_NEW_FEATURE_FLAG.

    public function up()
    {
        FeatureFlag::create([
            'name' => 'MY_NEW_FEATURE_FLAG',
            'description' => 'Concise description of your new feature flag',
            'active' => 0
        ]);
    }


Create a constant pointing to your new feature flag on FeatureFlag model:

class FeatureFlag extends Model
{
...
public const NEW_FEATURE_FLAG = 'MY_NEW_FEATURE_FLAG';
...
}

Usage

Wherever you need to check the status of a feature flag, you can use isActive() method.

$isMyFeatureFlagActive = FeatureFlag::isActive(
    FeatureFlag::MY_NEW_FEATURE_FLAG
);

Composer Nightmare

If we ever find ourselves in a situation where an author of a composer package decides to delete it, we can follow these steps to bring it back:


For this document, I will reference the payavel/checkout package as an example.


Step 1: Retrieve the latest version of the code.

Copy the contents of /vendor/payavel/checkout to {WHEREVER_YOU_LIKE}/incfile/checkout

This does require that you have the incfile/atomic repository on your machine, otherwise, you will need to reach out to the production server to retrieve the package from there (or ask a fellow developer that actually works ).


Step 2: Initializing git

Head to the directory where you copied the code form step 1 & initiate a new git repository.

git init

Step 3: Publish the repository under incfile's account.

First create a new "blank" repository with incfile's github account. You may name it however you wish; I recommend keeping the same name to avoid confusion.


Then you must follow the steps in github in order to add the origin remote to the local repository you initiated in step 2.

git remote add origin git@github.com:incfile/checkout.git

And then push the repo to the master branch.

git push origin master

Step 4: Publish a release for the package.

Before we do this, it is recommended to update the package's composer.json file to reflect that incfile is the current owner of this package and it will be easily identifiable in atomic. To achieve this, you can follow these steps.

We can publish new releases in github, in this example I am using payavel/checkout, but you can update the url's by just changing the repository's name.


First, head to https://github.com/incfile/checkout/releases/new. You should see something like this:

You can go ahead and create a new tag, in this case I will be tagging v1.0.0, and the release title will be v1.0.0 as well. You may also add a description if you wish & publish the release.


Step 5: Direct atomic's composer.json the look for the new package.

First, you must add the following snippet to the composer.json file under the "repositories" option.

"repositories": [
    {
      "type": "vcs",
      "url": "git@github.com:incfile/checkout"
    }
]

Now you can run composer update payavel/checkout (being the original package name) and it should pull the code from the package you just created.


If you did rename the package ownership, you must remove the previous package and then require the new one under the new owner's name (incfile/checkout).


And Voila! Everything should now work as expected.


Changing package ownership (optional).

If you would like to assume ownership of the package, there is one additional step we need to follow.


Head to the package's composer.json file and update the old owner's name to incfile.

{
  "name": "payavel/checkout",
  "name": "incfile/checkout",
}

And push these changes to the package's repository.

Incfile currently supports many types of addresses:

  • Client (Contact)

  • Company

  • EIN (SS4)

  • Registered Agent

  • Foreign Qualification

  • Billing


Many or even all of the previous 👆🏼 addresses could be the same. To keep our data consistent and give the client a great user experience, we have developed an address management module where the client may create, read, update, and delete (CRUD) his addresses.


Data Layer

Tables

The addresses module comprises four tables: countries, states, cities & addresses. This brings us a lot of advantages related to the integrity of the data and prevents address duplication. It also brings us many advantages related to reporting.



Take a look at the database model for this section:



Models

We have prepared an eloquent model for each one of the tables above 👆🏼, which can be found in the App\Models\Address folder under Country::class, State::class, City::class & Address::class. These models have some predefined Accessors and Mutators in order to keep the data consistent and well-formatted, this is why we discourage the use raw database queries and the use of the query builder, instead, we encourage to always use Eloquent to manage this data.


Other Considerations

The State::class & City::class models uses Private (https://app.clickup.com/2403958/docs/29bkp-891/29bkp-882)which will add a global verification scope to the models that filters from the query all instances that have not been verified yet, if you wish to include those instances queue should add withUnverified() method to the query.


The Address::class model relates directly to a Client::class, this is to have a direct relationship with the owner/creator of that address.

Common Helpers

Laravel Helpers

This file contains several helper functions that can be used across the Laravel application. Helpers are found on the App\Models\Common there is no particular reason why they are placed here.


Most referenced Helpers

These helpers are the most used in the project; here is the functionality.

Function

Description

orderTypeWords

This function determines the order type name based on the order object passed as an argument. It applies various checks and updates to the order type name based on the order's origin, type, and predefined values. If the order type is not found in the predefined values, it looks for a value named 'browse' in the $_POST array and returns its value as the order type name if found. The final output is the order type name.

miscOrderWords

This function returns an array with predefined key-value pairs where each key represents a data type, and its corresponding value is the miscellaneous order type name.

getCountyFromZip

This function is simply a wrapper for the getCounty method in the Ziptastic class of the App\Models namespace. It calls the getCounty method with the given ZIP code and returns the county name if it exists in the response; otherwise, it returns null.

siteName

Replaces certain substrings in the hostname with their capitalized versions, if the hostname is incfile.com, will return the string "IncFile", if the hostname is maxfilings.com, will return "MaxFilings".

appName

Returns the current application's name based on the webroot directory name or the dev_name value stored in the WhiteLabel object in the cache memory. If the dev_name is stored in the cache memory, the current application is a whitelabel version of the original application, and the dev_name value is used instead of the webroot directory name.

stateList

This function returns an array of US state codes and their corresponding names.

getStatusOrderNumber

This function returns the order number of the given order status as it is stored in the database.

origin2app

This function takes an origin integer and returns the dev_name associated with that origin from the WhiteLabel model. It's useful for converting origin data into a more human-readable format.

incfilePriceList

This function returns an array of prices for various services

incfileServiceFeesByState

This function retrieves the appropriate Incfile service fee based on the $longState and $orderType.

getIncfileServiceFee


The function checks if the order type is a miscellaneous order with a dynamic fee, and if so, returns the service fee based on the state. Otherwise, the function uses a switch statement to return the service fee based on the order type and, in some cases, the entity type.

incfileDomain

This function returns a string that represents the URL of the Incfile website based on the environment it is running on. If it is running on a production environment, it returns the URL. 'https://www.incfile.com'. If it is running on a development environment, it reads the Git branch and Git owner URL in the format of. "https://incfile.{branch}.{user}.test.incfile.me". If the application is not running on production or development, it returns. 'https://incfile.cool'.

originFullDomain

This takes an integer parameter named $origin and returns a string value. It uses a Redis cache to store and retrieve the domain information. If the application runs in production mode retrieves the domain value for the given $origin value using the WhiteLabel model; if it is running in development constructs the domain name using the self::originName($origin), the contents of the .gitowner and .gitbranch files in the application's base path, and the constant string test.incfile.me.

originDashboardUrl

This method calls the originFullDomain method, which returns the full domain for a given origin.

originName

The method takes an integer parameter $origin that represents the ID of the origin. The method returns a string representing the proper name of the origin, which is fetched from a cache using RedisStore, and if the name is not already cached, it is retrieved from the database using the ID. The method uses an anonymous function that calls the WhiteLabel::find() method with the $origin parameter to retrieve the proper name from the database. If the name is successfully retrieved from the database, it is cached using RedisStore with an expiration time of 300 seconds.

shortState

The shortState function takes a string argument longState, which is the full name of a US state (e.g. "New York" or "Florida"), and returns a string that represents the two-letter abbreviation of that state (e.g. "NY" or "FL"). If the input string is not a valid state name, the function returns the input string itself. The function also trims any whitespace in the input string and converts it to all uppercase.

longState

The longState function takes a string argument state, which is the two-letter abbreviation of a US state (e.g. "NY" or "FL"), and returns a string that represents the full name of that state (e.g. "New York" or "Florida"). If the input string is not a valid state abbreviation, the function returns it. The function also converts the input string to all uppercase.

percentComplete

This function returns an array that contains the percentage complete for various stages of an order process. The function takes no arguments, reads an entityType value from a main order model, and populates the $percent array with percentages for various stages of the order process, depending on the value of entityType.

estimateExpeditedDate

This function takes an order date and a filing time as parameters and returns an estimated expedited date. The order date is when the order was placed, and the filing time is required to process the order. The filing time is passed as a string and can be weeks or days.


This function is specific to 2018; the listed holidays and free weekdays are hard-coded. This means that it may not be accurate for other years or locations.

dateDiff

This function calculates the number of days between two dates. The input parameters are $start and $end, which are the start and end dates respectively. The function calculates the difference between the timestamps, which gives the number of seconds between the two dates. Finally, it divides the number of seconds by the number of seconds in a day (86400) and rounds the result to the nearest whole number using the round function. The result is the number of days between the two dates.

orderStatusLists

This function returns an array of order status options. Each option is represented by a key-value pair, where the key is an integer and the value is a string describing the status.

getOfferServiceLink

This function generates a URL for ordering an annual report service based on the provided parameters. The function checks if the service is being offered, generates a URL based on the order origin and sets the link variable to /annual-report.php. After generating the URL, the function checks if $disable parameter is true. If so, it generates a route to the dashboard and adds orderId and dueDate parameters to the URL.

fetchUpcomingNotifications

This function returns an array of upcoming compliance notifications based on the provided data and suborders.

statesRequiredCompanyAddress

The statesRequiredCompanyAddress function takes in the entity state and entity type as parameters, and returns an array of state codes that require a company address for the given entity type.

getOrderFAQ

This returns the FAQ content for an ancillary order, reads the FAQ content from a JSON file located and decodes it into an associative array, if $search and $replace are provided, the method replaces all occurrences of the strings in $search with their corresponding values in $replace using the str_replace() function before returning the FAQ content.

getStateFillingRequirementByField



This takes a state name and a field name as inputs and returns the value of the requested field for the given state. It queries the state_filling_requirement table in the database and returns the value of the requested field from the first result. If the value is not set, it returns an empty string.

returnAncillaryOrderMutex

This returns a string used as a mutex key for ancillary orders. It checks if the order type belongs to a list of specific types that can have different states, and if so, it creates a key with the company, order type, and state. Otherwise, it creates a key with the company and order type.

returnAncillaryThankyouView

This returns the view for the ancillary order thank you page. It takes the order number, order type, revenue, and a boolean value indicating whether or not the Google Tag Manager should fire. It sets the order data and shares the data with the view. If there is a user with no orders, it redirects to the ancillary created page, passing the order data as parameters. Otherwise, it determines which view to use based on whether it is a dashboard.

trimExtraSpace

This removes extra spaces in a given string using the preg_replace function. It replaces any sequence of one or more spaces with a single space and returns the resulting string.

buildResponsePayload

This takes a status, a code, and an optional data array as inputs and returns an array containing the status, code, and message corresponding to the code from a configuration file. The data array is merged into this array using array_merge.

allowsEntityAsMember

The function checks whether a certain entity type is allowed as a member for a given state by retrieving the value of a specific field from the state_filling_requirement table. The field's name is constructed based on the entity type by concatenating the string "allows_member_entity_" with the result of calling getStateFillingRequirementFieldSuffix() with the entity type as an argument.

actionsRequiredList

The function returns an array of actions required for a specific order. The actions are represented as strings; each assigned an integer identifier.

logLastQuery

The function logs the last SQL query executed by the application and additional information, such as the event that triggered the query, the execution time, and any query parameters. The function uses Laravel's database query logging feature, which records all executed SQL queries for debugging purposes.

getAbbreviatedAddress

This function returns an abbreviated version of an address by replacing the words "street" and "suite" with their abbreviated versions "st" and "ste", respectively.

expeditedPrice

This function takes in an entity state and type, and returns an array of prices for different processing speeds, including the expedited price. The function looks up the prices in a pricesByState array using the entity state and type.

businessTypeList

This function returns a list of business types and licenses. It fetches the list of business industries and their licenses from the database using Eloquent ORM and constructs an array of business types and their licenses.

isCountyToolRequiredOnPage

Checks if a county tool is required for a given state and page. This method caches the result for 5 minutes using Redis.

formatPhoneNumber

Formats a given phone number string to have hyphens separating the area code, exchange, and subscriber numbers.

extractNumberString

Extracts a phone number or SSN string into an array of its component parts using the specified separator.

cleanPhoneNumber

Removes special characters from a phone number string.

formatFullAddress

Formats an address given an array of address fields, a prefix for the field names, and a boolean indicating whether to use <br> tags for line breaks. This method also formats the state field based on the country, using a separate shortState() method.

concatName

This method receives an array of fields and a prefix string as arguments. It concatenates the first and last name fields with the prefix to create a formatted contact name. The first name field returns an empty string if it is not set.

officersDetails

This method receives an object $order, a string $type, and an object $field as arguments. It returns the specified field's value from the order's officers data. If the field is not set in the officers data, it looks for it in the parent data.

isStateRequireOfficerAddress

This method receives a state and an optional $field string as arguments. It returns a boolean indicating whether the state requires or not an office address. It uses another method called getStateFillingRequirementByField() to get the filling requirements for the specified field.

getCountryDialCode

This method receives a country code and returns the corresponding dial code for that country. It gets the list of countries from another method called countriesList() and looks for the country with the specified code to get its dial code.

dbOrdernumFormat

This method receives an order number and formats it to highlight the four digits in the middle of the number. It replaces those digits with an HTML span tag to color and bold them.









Traits


Model Verification

Sometimes you might want to verify a model instance to know that the data being queried is valid; you may take advantage of the App\Scopes\Traits\IsVerified trait in the model you wish to have the verification functionalities.


This will add the app/Scopes/VerifiedScope::class global scope to your model.

In order for everything to work as expected, you must also add a verified_at column to your model's table:

Schema::create('users', function (Blueprint $table) {
  $table->bigIncrements('id');
  $table->string('email')->unique();
  $table->timestamp('verified_at')->nullable(); // This column is required
  // ...
});


Next, you may implement your verification logic as you wish and once the model is verified you may assign a timestamp value to the verified_at column of your model.

Hiring New Talent


Technical Interview

👨‍💼

Project Manager to present agenda and kick-off meeting.


Meeting Agenda:

  1. Introductions: (10 min)

    1. Company Introduction (5 mins): Interviewer introduces the company, team, and role. Briefly discusses the company culture, projects, and technologies used.

    2. Candidate Introduction (5 mins): Share brief professional background, and highlight relevant experiences.

  2. Behavioral Questions (15-20 mins)

    1. Teamwork experience (10 mins): Discuss the candidate's experience working in a team and ask about specific problems they have faced.

    2. Professional development (10 mins): Discuss the candidate's past and future professional development.

  3. Challenge Review (30 - 45 mins)

    1. Challenge Review (5 mins): Provide constructive feedback to candidate regarding the submitted challenge & potentially opens short discussion about his approach to solving the problem.

    2. Technical questions. (5-10 mins): Ask questions exploring their decision-making process and understanding of best practices. Discuss PHP and backend-specific topics such as design patterns, performance optimization, and database interactions.

    3. Short pair programming session (20-30 mins): Extend or refine the candidate's solution, discuss and implement improvements or an additional feature.

  4. Outro: (5-10mins)

    1. Candidate questions (5-10 mins): Ask questions & receive answers in english.

    2. Next steps (1 min)


Tips for the interview:

  • Ensure the environment is prepared for a smooth pair programming session (stable internet, necessary tools). Have your local environment up & running.

  • Be mindful of time to ensure all sections are covered without rushing.

  • Relax and don’t stress yourself. Good luck!

CoverDash

Background

Bizee partnered with CoverDash to allow users to compare quotes and purchase policies from more than 30 of the nation's largest insurers instantly. Through the CoverDash embedded tool, our customers will be able to find tailored coverage at industry leading prices on their Bizee dashboard in seconds.


Core Features

Instant Insurance Quotes and Quote Comparison

CoverDash allows users to get insurance quotes and compare them with multiple top-rated insurers in a matter of minutes. This feature provides business owners with the flexibility to select the best insurance coverage suited to their needs and budget without engaging with multiple brokers or companies individually.


AI-Powered Solutions

CoverDash uses advanced algorithms to match businesses with appropriate policies.


Wide Range of Coverage Options

CoverDash offers various insurance policies tailored to different business types, including:


  • General Liability: Protection from common business risks, such as customer injuries and property damage.

  • Professional Liability (E&O): Coverage for legal disputes resulting from negligence or unfulfilled tasks.

  • Cyber Insurance: Protects against data breaches, cyberattacks, and phishing incidents.

  • Workers’ Compensation: Coverage for employee injuries or illnesses directly resulting from employment.


Simplified Policy Management

Users have access to a personalized dashboard where they can manage their insurance policies in real-time. This includes generating certificates of insurance (COIs), monitoring coverage status, and accessing key policy details without needing to contact customer support . Policies are customizable, tailored to suit different business needs.


Cybersecurity Protection

One of CoverDash’s standout features is its Cyber Insurance, which provides protection from malicious cyberattacks, data breaches, ransomware, and phishing incidents. This is crucial for businesses operating online, such as e-commerce platforms or tech startups .


Embedded Insurance Solutions

For businesses that operate digital platforms (e.g., e-commerce or SaaS), CoverDash offers an embedded insurance solution. With a simple line of code, businesses can integrate CoverDash’s insurance features directly into their platform, enabling them to offer quotes and insurance options to their own customers .


Paperless Process

From quote to policy management, the entire process is done online.


Benefits of Using CoverDash

  • Time-Efficient: CoverDash saves users time by streamlining the entire insurance process—from comparing quotes to managing policies—all online.

  • Cost-Effective: The platform provides a range of competitive quotes, allowing users to find affordable options for various coverage types.

  • Comprehensive Protection: The variety of insurance options offered ensures that businesses can protect themselves from a wide array of risks, whether they need liability coverage, cyber protection, or workers’ compensation.


Target Audience

CoverDash is designed for:


  • Small Business Owners: Those running brick-and-mortar stores or offering professional services.

  • Freelancers and Independent Contractors: Individuals needing flexible insurance options for project-based work.

  • Online Business Owners: E-commerce merchants and tech startups who require cyber and general liability coverage.


CoverDash is a modern solution that offers a hassle-free approach to securing business insurance. Its easy-to-use platform, comprehensive insurance options, and instant quote comparison make it ideal for small business owners looking to protect their operations from potential risks.
